<DocsLayout title="C++ Coding & Output Questions" section="Question Banks" description="30 tricky C++ questions covering virtual dispatch, object slicing, move semantics, and undefined behavior">
  <h2 id="q1">Q1: What does this print?</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;iostream&gt;
struct Base {"{"}
    virtual void foo() {"{"} std::cout &lt;&lt; "Base\\n"; {"}"}
    ~Base() {"{"} foo(); {"}"} // Non-virtual destructor calling virtual
{"}"};
struct Derived : Base {"{"}
    void foo() override {"{"} std::cout &lt;&lt; "Derived\\n"; {"}"}
{"}"};
int main() {"{"} Derived d; {"}"}</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Answer:</strong> Prints "Base" during destruction, the dynamic type reverts to the current class being destroyed. Virtual dispatch in destructors calls the base version.</p>

  <h2 id="q2">Q2: Move Semantics Trap</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-cpp">std::string a = "hello";
std::string b = std::move(a);
std::cout &lt;&lt; a.size();  // What value?</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Answer:</strong> Implementation-defined but valid. After move, <code>a</code> is in a valid-but-unspecified state. Most implementations: 0.</p>

  <h2 id="q3">Q3: RAII and Exception Safety</h2>
  <p><strong>Question:</strong> Design a thread-safe singleton using RAII that is exception-safe during construction.</p>
  <p><strong>Expected:</strong> Meyer's Singleton with static local (C++11 guarantees thread-safe initialization). Discuss double-checked locking anti-pattern.</p>

